WEBVTT

00:00:00.880 --> 00:00:05.200
My name is Gordon Shotwell. I'm a software engineer on the Shiny team at Posit.

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:14.560
Well, we just announced that Shiny for Python is out of alpha. It's available for everyone.

00:00:14.560 --> 00:00:25.680
The API is stable. Shiny for Python is the Python version of our popular R library for

00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:31.520
building interactive web applications, mainly focused on data science web applications. It's

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:36.880
written 100% in Python. There's no R code in the library. I think it sort of adds a lot of

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:40.400
power and flexibility to the Python web application landscape.

00:00:43.119 --> 00:00:49.599
So Shiny for Python is being introduced because we saw a gap in the Python web application

00:00:49.599 --> 00:00:54.480
landscape. I really felt this in my own work when I was kind of trying to transition a lot of

00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:59.599
Shiny for R apps to Python, and there wasn't really anything that I could find that did all

00:00:59.599 --> 00:01:04.239
the things that we needed the framework to do. And so Shiny for Python lets you kind of gives

00:01:04.239 --> 00:01:09.440
you a single framework that can handle a big range of complexity from very, very simple apps to very,

00:01:09.440 --> 00:01:14.559
very complicated ones without needing to learn a new thing or fundamentally change how you're

00:01:14.559 --> 00:01:21.120
developing the application. So for the most part, the popular kind of Python web application

00:01:21.120 --> 00:01:27.120
frameworks are really narrowly focused on a single, I guess I would call it range of complexity

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:33.440
for an application. For example, Streamlit, it's really focused on that first experience of

00:01:33.440 --> 00:01:37.919
running a web application, moving from a script that you're writing on your computer to an

00:01:37.919 --> 00:01:42.800
initial web app. But what you kind of discover as you work with it a little bit more is that

00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:48.639
the framework gets really, really difficult to use as your application gets much more complicated,

00:01:48.639 --> 00:01:52.720
which often causes people to maybe start developing something in Streamlit and then have

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:58.239
to sort of stop and move to another framework or ask another group of people at their organization

00:01:58.239 --> 00:02:04.000
to develop a quote-unquote real web app. And Shiny takes a different approach, which is that it

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:10.399
gives you a set of tools or a set of concepts that can accommodate a big range of different

00:02:10.399 --> 00:02:14.800
types of complexity. So it's something that, you know, you can teach a new person in an afternoon,

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:20.720
you can spin up a tiny Shiny app to test a statistical concept for yourself, but it can

00:02:20.720 --> 00:02:25.919
also handle very, very complicated applications, which normally you might need to use something

00:02:25.919 --> 00:02:32.080
like a JavaScript framework or Flask or Django to really accomplish. So that's the main thing it

00:02:32.080 --> 00:02:38.639
adds to the landscape is this ability to be sort of simple, but also know that they also

00:02:38.639 --> 00:02:46.639
give you the tools to accomplish really, really difficult tasks. The main strength of Shiny is

00:02:46.639 --> 00:02:51.039
reactivity, and what that means is that the only things that re-render in a Shiny app are the

00:02:51.039 --> 00:02:55.839
things that need to re-render. So it doesn't run the application code top to bottom, it just

00:02:56.559 --> 00:03:00.399
keeps track of the relationships between all the different inputs and outputs in your application

00:03:01.119 --> 00:03:07.279
and re-renders the outputs which need to re-render if an input changes. What reactivity means is that

00:03:07.279 --> 00:03:14.080
when you're writing an application, you basically kind of decorate various different function calls

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:19.119
which generate a relationship between all of those different function calls. So this ends up as a

00:03:19.119 --> 00:03:24.160
what's called a computation graph. And the main virtue of computational graphs is that you can

00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:28.880
minimally re-render them so the application can do the smallest amount of work that it needs to do

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:33.839
to generate the right output. What makes this very powerful for Shiny is that if you have, for example,

00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:39.039
a multi-page app with many different components, the only components that actually cause your

00:03:39.039 --> 00:03:43.839
computer to do anything are the ones that are visible to the user. So this kind of means that

00:03:43.839 --> 00:03:50.240
you can have apps load fast initially, and then you can put expensive computations in places that

00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:56.639
people don't necessarily go to right away to speed up the overall user experience. So reactivity

00:03:58.880 --> 00:04:03.119
hits this sweet spot where it allows you to accommodate really, really complex things,

00:04:03.119 --> 00:04:06.160
but your code doesn't really need to be that complicated because most of the work

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:12.399
about the wiring and how those relationships are generated between the different components

00:04:12.399 --> 00:04:16.320
is really a side effect of writing the application. It's not something you need to

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:23.839
think about that much, especially for a beginner. Streamlet is a web application framework that

00:04:23.839 --> 00:04:28.959
allows you to take an existing Python script and add special function calls that turn it into

00:04:29.279 --> 00:04:35.920
interactive web application. And the main virtue of Streamlet is that it's a really natural next

00:04:35.920 --> 00:04:42.160
step from developing a Python script. So the idea behind Streamlet is you take your existing Python

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:48.079
script, and just by adding some functions to that script, it turns it into a web application. So you

00:04:48.079 --> 00:04:54.160
don't need to reorganize your code very much initially to get something that does run as a

00:04:54.160 --> 00:05:00.160
useful interactive web application. So that initial experience is very good. The app looks

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:06.239
very nice right out of the gate. And the main thing is that for the brand new user, they're

00:05:06.239 --> 00:05:09.920
not asked to learn very much to start with Streamlet. And that's kind of, I think, one of

00:05:09.920 --> 00:05:15.200
the main reasons why it's been such a phenomenally successful company. The main technical difference

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:21.119
between Shiny and Streamlet is that Streamlet re-renders the whole application code start to

00:05:21.119 --> 00:05:27.839
finish every time any input changes. Whereas Shiny only re-executes the parts of the application

00:05:27.839 --> 00:05:33.440
that need to be executed in order to display something. So this kind of comes up a lot of

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:38.959
times when you maybe have a plot, which is based on reading in a big dataset. If you change some

00:05:38.959 --> 00:05:45.040
option that just affects how the plot looks, like the color or the scales, by default, Streamlet

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:48.720
will just read in the whole application again. It'll start from the very beginning of the script

00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:54.559
and read the whole thing. So there's various different ways of accommodating that on a

00:05:54.559 --> 00:05:59.760
Streamlet application and avoiding that problem of just reading in everything all the time.

00:06:00.559 --> 00:06:04.959
But all of them kind of add a lot of complexity to the application. So Streamlet apps, I would

00:06:04.959 --> 00:06:10.880
say, they start easy and end hard. So that as the app grows in complexity, the things that you have

00:06:10.880 --> 00:06:17.119
to do to get it to work become really difficult and it stops being actually an easy experience.

00:06:17.920 --> 00:06:23.200
Shiny takes a different approach, which is that because it has this sort of reactive framework,

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:29.200
you have to reorganize your code a little bit to get it to work initially. So that very,

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:34.239
very first experience, you have to learn a little bit to get there. But the lessons that

00:06:34.239 --> 00:06:39.359
you learn at the beginning will carry you all the way through your application's journey,

00:06:39.359 --> 00:06:43.679
its lifecycle. So there's never a point once you kind of have a Shiny app running

00:06:44.239 --> 00:06:50.959
where the next ask, the next question becomes this monumental task that requires you to

00:06:50.959 --> 00:06:58.000
refactor your application. So the way that it accomplishes that is by executing things

00:06:59.279 --> 00:07:04.160
in a computation graph instead of re-rendering everything whenever anything changes.

00:07:06.320 --> 00:07:11.440
So there's a few strengths of Shiny for Python. So one of them is Shiny applications are websites.

00:07:11.519 --> 00:07:15.839
So they're simple, like at the front end, it's a simple HTML site, which means that

00:07:16.640 --> 00:07:21.200
all of the sort of HTML or JavaScript knowledge that you or your team can bring to bear on the

00:07:21.200 --> 00:07:28.160
problem can be used right away. Similarly, if you have an existing R app that has some CSS,

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:34.000
that CSS should work, should be imported, should be importable without modification

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:38.799
to your Shiny for Python app. Streamlit, by contrast, their way that they kind of run

00:07:39.519 --> 00:07:45.519
styling means that it's much more difficult to add truly customized user experiences on top of it.

00:07:45.519 --> 00:07:50.640
It's kind of optimized for making the initial app look really good and have some small changes that

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:55.040
you can make. But if you really want to make a customized sort of look and feel of your application,

00:07:55.040 --> 00:08:00.559
it becomes pretty difficult. The second main thing is the relative computational efficiency of Shiny

00:08:00.559 --> 00:08:04.799
over Streamlit. So because Streamlit has made the choice to run everything start to finish,

00:08:04.799 --> 00:08:09.359
you kind of necessarily are going to have code which is running, which doesn't strictly speaking

00:08:09.359 --> 00:08:15.679
need to run in order to display the correct output for a given set of inputs. Shiny, by contrast,

00:08:15.679 --> 00:08:21.279
minimally re-renders components, which means that you don't really need to think so hard about

00:08:21.279 --> 00:08:27.440
how your app is connected to itself or making sure that only the right things are cached.

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:32.559
Shiny handles all of that for you. So with Streamlit, in order to build a kind of complicated

00:08:32.559 --> 00:08:38.159
app or app that reads in large data sets, you usually have to kind of manually manage callback

00:08:38.159 --> 00:08:42.799
functions or caching and caching validation, which can turn into a bit of a headache if you want to

00:08:42.799 --> 00:08:48.799
get a performant application. So of course, all of these things to some degree are a matter of taste,

00:08:48.799 --> 00:08:53.440
like what people find difficult or not. But if you have experienced some of these problems with

00:08:53.440 --> 00:08:59.200
Streamlit, you found that execution model limiting or you found caching or callbacks confusing or

00:08:59.200 --> 00:09:04.719
fraught with bugs, I'd really encourage you to give Shiny a try. We're a new framework in this

00:09:04.719 --> 00:09:09.520
world, but we think we do have something really special to offer and we'd love your feedback on it.

00:09:11.840 --> 00:09:17.679
So Dash is a slightly older framework in the Python ecosystem, a web application framework

00:09:17.679 --> 00:09:22.799
that's built around this idea of stateless functions, which means that each callback or

00:09:22.799 --> 00:09:28.640
each thing that's creating a graph or a table is independent of all the other pieces. And

00:09:28.640 --> 00:09:33.520
its main goal, and it does, I think, a remarkably good job at accomplishing this goal, is to build

00:09:34.080 --> 00:09:40.080
applications which are really, really efficient to deploy. So I would say a lot of the

00:09:40.080 --> 00:09:45.760
things that Dash asks you to do as a developer are there so that the deployment of a Dash app

00:09:45.760 --> 00:09:51.840
and the way it's served by servers to the user is really, really efficient. And that's kind

00:09:51.840 --> 00:09:57.760
of the main thing that it optimizes for. The value of that is that it's easy to scale apps

00:09:57.760 --> 00:10:02.559
horizontally by adding a lot more servers, a lot more processes, and because you have

00:10:02.559 --> 00:10:07.599
these kind of independent callbacks. When you have done the work to develop a good Dash app,

00:10:07.599 --> 00:10:11.919
you've gone through that process, the app that you end up with is really, really efficient to serve

00:10:11.919 --> 00:10:18.080
to users. So the kind of user experience is fast, and most importantly, the process of scaling

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:26.799
that app is really, really easy for a DevOps person. So stateful versus stateless. So stateful

00:10:26.799 --> 00:10:32.559
apps are apps where the server is kind of maintaining some information about the user

00:10:32.559 --> 00:10:36.799
session. Mostly when you're working on a script on your computer, you have some kind of global

00:10:36.799 --> 00:10:42.400
variable or information that is passed, that is held in memory on your computer and passed to a

00:10:42.400 --> 00:10:47.280
bunch of different functions. So in stateful applications, that information is held in memory

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:53.840
by the server, and it's passed to the individual function calls. Stateless applications take a

00:10:53.840 --> 00:10:58.799
different approach, which is that the server is not maintaining any kind of state about the user,

00:10:58.799 --> 00:11:04.320
like each component of the app kind of needs to go from start to finish to deliver that particular

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:08.880
graph. So if you have three graphs or three different components being rendered on a website

00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:14.320
in a stateless framework, they might each read in a data set, each read in the same data set

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:22.000
in order to generate that component. And the value of that is that multithreading becomes really,

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:27.039
really easy because you don't need to keep any of those components in sync. You could have one

00:11:27.039 --> 00:11:31.679
application, one session, user session be served by three or 15 different servers. They can be served

00:11:31.679 --> 00:11:37.440
by servers in different countries, and it doesn't really matter. The issue with developing stateless

00:11:37.440 --> 00:11:43.119
applications is that it's not how you usually program. So if you're programming on your computer,

00:11:43.760 --> 00:11:50.559
you usually are dealing with one process on one laptop, one computer. And as a result,

00:11:50.559 --> 00:11:58.080
it's really natural to use variables to store information in server state and to have functions

00:11:58.080 --> 00:12:03.760
read data in one place and have it be used in many places by rendering functions. And so when

00:12:03.760 --> 00:12:08.640
you're moving from that sort of stateful way that you've been developing a project to a stateless

00:12:08.640 --> 00:12:13.919
dash application, it can be really painful, and you end up needing to do quite a lot of work

00:12:13.919 --> 00:12:19.359
to move your process into that world in a kind of reasonably efficient way.

00:12:21.039 --> 00:12:26.159
When you compare Shiny to Dash, the main thing that Shiny has is just a richer set of server

00:12:26.159 --> 00:12:32.479
states. Shiny is stateful, and what that means is that you can read data in one place, you can have

00:12:33.039 --> 00:12:38.159
reactive calculation that does some work on it, and then pass the result of that reactive

00:12:38.159 --> 00:12:42.719
calculation to as many different rendering functions as you want. So it really does a

00:12:42.719 --> 00:12:46.960
better job of respecting the kind of do-not-repeat-yourself principle of computer programming,

00:12:46.960 --> 00:12:52.320
where you're reading the data in one place, you're processing it in another function, and passing it

00:12:52.320 --> 00:12:58.159
to rendering functions only afterwards. With Dash, you kind of are forced, if you have like an

00:12:58.159 --> 00:13:02.400
application with three graphs, you have a couple of choices that you can make. You can have

00:13:02.960 --> 00:13:08.799
three functions which each read and process the data, or you can have one sort of mega function

00:13:08.799 --> 00:13:14.799
that reads in the data and then updates all three plots. And both of them are kind of a little

00:13:14.799 --> 00:13:20.000
awkward because that's not usually how you're used to developing applications. Usually what

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:24.960
you want to do is have each function do one thing and do it well, and you want to have each

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:29.119
calculation happen in one place. You don't want to have that code be repeated anywhere in your

00:13:29.119 --> 00:13:34.880
application. And when you're moving to Dash, you kind of have to pick between a few options,

00:13:34.880 --> 00:13:36.640
none of which are terribly appealing.

00:13:39.200 --> 00:13:44.640
So whenever I've developed a web application, usually I need to start developing it very,

00:13:44.640 --> 00:13:50.559
very quickly. I have almost no time to get a minimal thing out the door. But it never stays

00:13:50.559 --> 00:13:56.080
simple. It always gets more complicated. There's another ask, there's another requirement from some

00:13:56.080 --> 00:14:02.159
user, and the application slowly becomes more complicated. It's used by more people, more people

00:14:02.159 --> 00:14:07.840
want more things from it. So our design philosophy for Shiny is that we want Shiny to support any of

00:14:07.840 --> 00:14:12.400
those asks. So even though it's something that you can start, get something up in an afternoon

00:14:12.960 --> 00:14:17.760
or a couple of hours, you know that you have all the tools to make it a business-critical

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:23.359
web application that's used by many, many people. And we don't want you to end up in a place where

00:14:23.359 --> 00:14:27.520
there's some task, something you really want this application to do, and the framework just won't

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:33.119
let you do it. So that's kind of what we mean when we say that it strikes a great balance between

00:14:33.119 --> 00:14:40.960
simplicity and complexity. It starts simple, but that application can grow to accomplish

00:14:40.960 --> 00:14:45.359
really, really complicated problems without needing to sort of fight the framework.

00:14:47.359 --> 00:14:52.559
To sum up, most of the popular Python web application frameworks are focused on a kind

00:14:52.559 --> 00:14:57.919
of narrow band of problem complexity. Streamlit is focused on your initial application just right

00:14:57.919 --> 00:15:04.400
when you start. Dash is focused on applications which are where deployment efficiency is really,

00:15:04.400 --> 00:15:09.840
really important. There's not really a single framework that lets you grow from very, very

00:15:09.840 --> 00:15:15.440
simple problems to very, very complicated ones. The killer feature of Shiny is that it does support

00:15:15.440 --> 00:15:20.880
that type of complexity. So it's a simple set of principles to learn about building your initial

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:24.719
Shiny app, but once you learn them, you don't really need to change them as your problem gets

00:15:24.719 --> 00:15:31.280
more complicated. It supports a full range of CSS and JavaScript customization and also has an

00:15:31.280 --> 00:15:36.640
execution model that's efficient enough to handle data science web applications, which can often be

00:15:36.640 --> 00:15:42.960
quite computationally intensive. Our main hope is that you all try this framework, let us know what

00:15:42.960 --> 00:15:47.679
works and what doesn't, show us what you're building with it, and help us develop some of the

00:15:47.679 --> 00:15:53.840
community contributions that we really need to make this a successful project. So give it a try

00:15:53.840 --> 00:16:06.719
and we can't wait to see what you build with it.

